\f1\b Definition of Random Variable (RV):
\f0\b0  A random variable $X$ on a sample space $\\Omega$ is a function $X: \\Omega \\rightarrow \\mathbb\{R\}$ that assigns a real number $X(\\omega)$ to each sample point $\\omega \\in \\Omega$.\uc0\u8232 
\fs22 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 +1
\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b Discrete Random Variables:
\f0\b0  These variables take values in a range that is either finite or countably infinite.\uc0\u8232 
\fs22 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 +1
\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b Discrete Subset:
\f0\b0  While $X$ maps to the set of real numbers ($\\mathbb\{R\}$), the actual set of values $\\\{X(\\omega): \\omega \\in \\Omega\\\}$ that $X$ takes is a discrete subset of $\\mathbb\{R\}$.\uc0\u8232 
\fs22 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 +1
\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
